

<section xml:id="Ch3Sec1DefinitionsExamples">
  <title>Definitions and Examples</title>

<subsection>
  <title>Definition of a linear map</title>
<!--
    <figure>
        <caption>Video recording for the intro to and definition of a linear map.</caption>
        <video source="https://learn.sun.ac.za/pluginfile.php/1653776/mod_folder/content/0/Lec16LinearMapIntroAndDefn.mp4" width="50%" preview="../latex/images/preview-doc-cam.jpg" onerror="this.src='Default.jpg'" />
    </figure>
-->
  <p>
    Recall that a <em>function</em>
    (or a <em>map</em>)
    <m>f : X \rightarrow Y</m> from a set <m>X</m> to a set <m>Y</m> is
    a rule which assigns to each element <m>x\in X</m> an element <m>f(x)</m> of <m>Y</m>.
    We write <m>x \mapsto f(x)</m> to indicate that an element <m>x \in X</m> maps to
    <m>f(x) \in Y</m> under the function <m>f</m>.
    See <xref ref="explanation_of_mapsto">Figure</xref>.
    Two functions <m>f, g : X \rightarrow Y</m> are <em>equal</em>
    if <m>f(x) = g(x)</m> for all <m>x</m> in <m>X</m>.
  </p>

  <figure xml:id="explanation_of_mapsto">
    <caption>A function <m>f : X \rightarrow Y</m>.</caption>
    <image width="60%">
      <latex-image>
        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}\draw (-2, 0) circle (1);
        \draw (2,0) circle (1);
        \node at (-2, -1.3) {\(X\)};
        \node at (2, -1.3) {\(Y\)};
        \draw[->] (-0.8, 0.3) to[out=30, in=150] node[above] {\(f\)} (0.8, 0.3);
        \node (a) at (-2, -0.5) {\(x\)};
        \node (b) at (2, -0.5) {\(f(x)\)};
        \draw[|->] (a) to[out=-20, in=200] (b);\end{tikzpicture}]]>
      </latex-image>
    </image>
  </figure>

  <definition>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>V</m> and <m>W</m> be vector spaces.
        A <term>linear map</term> from <m>V</m> to <m>W</m> is a function <m>T : V \rightarrow W</m> satisfying:

        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>T(\ve{v} + \ve{v}') = T(\ve{v}) + T(\ve{v}')</m> for all vectors <m>\ve{v}, \ve{v}' \in V</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>T(k \ve{v}) = k T (\ve{v})</m> for all vectors
              <m>\ve{v} \in V</m> and all scalars <m>k \in \mathbb{R}</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <note>
    <p>
      Another name for a linear map is a
      <em>linear transformation</em>.
    </p>
  </note>

</subsection>

<subsection>
  <title>Examples of linear maps</title>

  <example xml:id="matrices-give-rise-to-linear-maps-example">
    <title>Matrices give rise to linear maps</title>
    <statement>
<!--
      <figure>
        <caption>Video recording for <xref ref="matrices-give-rise-to-linear-maps-example"/>.</caption>
        <video source="https://learn.sun.ac.za/pluginfile.php/1653776/mod_folder/content/0/Lec16LinearMapDemo.mp4" width="70%" preview="../latex/images/preview-doc-cam.jpg" onerror="this.src='Default.jpg'" />
      </figure>
-->
      <p>
        Every <m>n \times m</m> matrix <m>\mat{A}</m> induces a <em>linear map</em>
        <md>
          <mrow>T_{\mat{A}} : \Col_m \amp  \rightarrow \Col_n</mrow>
          <mrow>\col{v} \amp  \mapsto \mat{A} \col{v} \, </mrow>
        </md>.
      </p>

      <p>
        That is, <m>T_{\mat{A}} (\col{v}) := \mat{A} \col{v}</m> is the matrix product of <m>\mat{A}</m> with the column vector <m>\col{v}</m>.
        The fact that <m>T_\mat{A}</m> is indeed a linear map follows from the linearity of matrix multiplication
        (<xref ref="props_of_matrix_ops">Proposition</xref> parts 2 and 3).
      </p>

      <p>
        Note that an <m>n \times m</m> matrix gives rise to a linear map from <m>\Col_m</m> to <m>\Col_n</m>!
      </p>

      <p>
        For instance, consider
        <me>
          A = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \\ 1 \amp -2 \end{bmatrix}
        </me>
        This gives rise to a linear map
        <md>
         <mrow> T : \Col_2 \amp \rightarrow \Col_2 </mrow>
         <mrow> \begin{bmatrix} v_1 \\ v_2 \end{bmatrix} \amp \mapsto \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \\ 1 \amp -2 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} v_1 \\ v_2 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
        </md>
        The following interactive Geogebra app demonstrates this. Drag the red vector <m>\col{v}</m> around to see the effect on <m>\mat{A} \col{v}</m>. You can also change the coefficients of the matrix <m>\mat{A}</m> by dragging the sliders.
      </p>
      <figure>
        <title>Geogebra app</title>
        <caption>  Interactive GeoGebra applet displaying the linear map <m>\col{v} \mapsto \mat{A}\col{v}</m>.</caption>
        <interactive geogebra="https://www.geogebra.org/material/iframe/id/vexfrzez/width/600/height/701/border/888888/sfsb/true/smb/false/stb/false/stbh/false/ai/false/asb/false/sri/false/rc/false/ld/false/sdz/false/ctl/false" aspect="600:701" width="90%"/>
      </figure>
    </statement>
  </example>

<example>
<title>A non-linear map</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      The following interactive JSXGraph applet illustrates the <q>polar coordinates</q> map
      <md>
        <mrow> T : \mathbb{R}^2 \amp \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^2 </mrow>
        <mrow> \begin{bmatrix} v_1 \\ v_2 \end{bmatrix} \amp \mapsto \begin{bmatrix} v_1 \cos(\pi v_2) \\ v_1 \sin(\pi v_2)  \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
      </md>
      Note that <m>T</m> is a non-linear map, since, for most points <m>\ve{v}, \ve{v}' \in \mathbb{R}^2</m>, we have <m>T(\ve{v} + \ve{v}') \neq T(\ve{v}) + T(\ve{v}')</m>.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <caption>Polar coordinates as a non-linear map.</caption>
      <interactive xml:id="interactive-polar-map" platform="jsxgraph" source="code/jsxgraph/PolarCoordMap.js" aspect="10:4">
        <sidebyside widths="40% 5% 40%" valign="middle">
          <slate xml:id="jsxgraph-polar-1" surface="jsxboard"/>
          <p><m> \xrightarrow{ \large T } </m></p>
          <slate xml:id="jsxgraph-polar-2" surface="jsxboard"/>
        </sidebyside>
        <instructions>
            <p>Drag the point <m>\ve{v}</m> to see the effect on <m>T(\ve{v})</m>.</p>
        </instructions>
      </interactive>
    </figure>
    <p>
      Another way to see that <m>T</m> is non-linear is that <m>T</m> does not send straight lines to straight lines.
    </p>
  </statement>
</example>

  <example>
    <title>Identity map</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>V</m> be a vector space.
        The function
        <md>
          <mrow>\id_V : V \amp \rightarrow V</mrow>
          <mrow>\ve{v} \amp  \mapsto \ve{v}</mrow>
        </md>
        is called the <em>identity map</em> on <m>V</m>.
        It is clearly a linear map, since
        <md>
          <mrow>\id_V (\ve{v} + \ve{w}) \amp = \ve{v} + \ve{w}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = \id_V (\ve{v}) + \id_V (\ve{w})</mrow>
        </md>
        and
        <md>
          <mrow>\id_V (k \ve{v}) \amp = k \ve{v}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = k \id_V (\ve{v})</mrow>
        </md>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>

  <example xml:id="projection_map_example">
    <title>Projection as a linear map</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
      The function
      <md>
        <mrow>T : \mathbb{R}^2 \amp \rightarrow \mathbb{R}</mrow>
        <mrow>(x, y) \amp \mapsto x</mrow>
      </md>
      which projects vectors onto the <m>x</m>-axis is a linear map.
    </p>

    <p>
      Let us check additivity algebraically:
      <me>
        T \left ( (x_1, y_1 ) + (x_2, y_2) \right) \stackrel{\text{?} }{=} T\left((x_1, y_1) \right) + T\left((x_2, y_2)\right)
      </me>
      <md>
        <mrow>\text{LHS}  \amp = T \left( (x_1 + x_2, y_1 + y_2) \right) \amp  \text{RHS}  \amp = x_1 + x_2</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = x_1 + x_2</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>

    <p>
      Here is a a graphical version of this proof:
    </p>

    <figure>
      <caption>
      </caption>
      <image width="70%">
        <latex-image>
          <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}[xscale=1.5]
          \draw[<->] (-1, 0) -- (3, 0);
          \draw[<->] (0, -1) -- (0, 3);
          \draw[very thick, primaryColor, ->] (0,0) -- node[above left] {\(\ve{v}\)} (0.5, 1) ;
          \draw[very thick, primaryColor, ->] (0.5,1) -- node[above left] {\(\ve{w}\)} (1.5, 1.5) ;
          \draw[dotted] (0.5, 1) -- (0.5, 0);
          \draw[dotted] (1.5, 1.5) -- (1.5, 0);
          \draw[very thick, primaryColor, ->] (0,0) -- node[below] {\(T(\ve{v})\)} (0.5, 0) ;
          \draw[very thick, primaryColor, ->] (0.5, 0) -- node[below] {\(T(\ve{w})\)} (1.5, 0) ;
          \node[primaryColor] at (2.3, 0.3) {\(T(\ve{v} + \ve{w})\)};
          \node[primaryColor] at (2.3, -0.3) {\(T(\ve{v}) + T(\ve{w})\)};\end{tikzpicture}]]>
        </latex-image>
      </image>
    </figure>
    </statement>
  </example>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Prove algebraically that we also have <m>T(k \ve{v}) = k T(\ve{v})</m>,
        so that <m>T</m> is a linear map.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        We only need to do the following computation:
        <me> T(k \ve v) = T(k(x,y)) = T(kx,ky) = kx = kT((x,y)) = kT(\ve v)  </me>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <example xml:id="rotation_as_linear_map">
    <title>Rotation as a linear map</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Fix an angle <m>\theta</m>.
        The function
        <md>
          <mrow>R_\theta : \mathbb{R}^2 \amp  \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^2</mrow>
          <mrow>\ve{v} \amp  \mapsto \text{rotation of } \ve{v} \text{ counterclockwise through angle }\theta</mrow>
        </md>
        is a linear map,
        by a similar graphical argument as in <xref ref="projection_map_example">Example</xref>.
      </p>

      <figure>
        <caption>
        </caption>
        <image width="40%">
          <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}\draw[<->] (-1, 0) -- (2, 0);
            \draw[<->] (0, -1) -- (0, 2);
            \draw[very thick, primaryColor, ->] (0,0) -- (30:1.5) node[right] {\(\ve{v}\)} ;
            \draw[very thick, primaryColor, ->] (0,0) --  (70:1.5) node[above] {\(R (\ve{v})\)};
            \draw (30:0.5) arc (30:70:0.5) node[xshift=2pt, yshift=2pt, right] {\(\theta\)} ;\end{tikzpicture}]]>
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>

    </statement>
  </example>

  <example xml:id="cross_prod_as_linear_map">
    <title>Cross product with a fixed vector as a linear map</title>
    <statement>
<!--
    <figure>
        <caption>Video recording for <xref ref="cross_prod_as_linear_map"/>.</caption>
        <video source="https://learn.sun.ac.za/pluginfile.php/1653776/mod_folder/content/0/Lec16CrossProduct.mp4" width="70%" preview="../latex/images/preview-doc-cam.jpg" onerror="this.src='Default.jpg'" />
    </figure>
-->
      <p>
        Fix a vector <m>\ve{w} \in \mathbb{R}^3</m>.
        The function
        <md>
          <mrow>C : \mathbb{R}^3 \amp \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^3</mrow>
          <mrow>\ve{v} \amp  \mapsto \ve{w} \times \ve{v}</mrow>
        </md>
        is a linear map because of the properties of the cross-product,
        <md>
          <mrow>\ve{w} \times (\ve{v}_1 + \ve{v}_2) \amp = \ve{w} \times \ve{v}_1 + \ve{w} \times \ve{v}_2</mrow>
          <mrow>\ve{w} \times (k \ve{v}) \amp = k \ve{w} \times \ve{v}</mrow>
        </md>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>

  <example xml:id="dot_prod_with_fix_vec">
    <title>Dot product with a fixed vector as a linear map</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Fix a vector <m>\ve{u} \in \mathbb{R}^3</m>.
        The function
        <md>
          <mrow>D : \mathbb{R}^3 \amp \rightarrow \mathbb{R}</mrow>
          <mrow>\ve{v} \amp  \mapsto \ve{u} \dotp \ve{v}</mrow>
        </md>
        (here <m>\cdot</m> is the dot product of vectors,
        not scalar multiplication!) is a linear map, because of the properties
        <md>
          <mrow>\ve{u} \dotp (\ve{v}_1 + \ve{v}_2) \amp = \ve{u} \dotp \ve{v}_1 + \ve{u} \smul\ve{v}_2</mrow>
          <mrow>\ve{u} \smul(k \ve{v}) \amp = k \ve{u} \dotp \ve{v}</mrow>
        </md>.
      </p>

        <p>
          We will soon see that <em>all</em>
          linear maps <m>\mathbb{R}^3 \rightarrow \mathbb{R}</m>
          (indeed all linear maps <m>\mathbb{R}^n \rightarrow \mathbb{R}</m>)
          are of this form.
        </p>

    </statement>
  </example>

  <example xml:id="diff_of_poly">
    <title>Differentiation as a linear map</title>
    <statement>
<!--
    <figure>
        <caption>Video recording for <xref ref="diff_of_poly"/>.</caption>
        <video source="https://learn.sun.ac.za/pluginfile.php/1653776/mod_folder/content/0/Lec16Differentiation.mp4" width="70%" preview="../latex/images/preview-doc-cam.jpg" onerror="this.src='Default.jpg'" />
    </figure>
-->
    <p>
      The operation <q>take the derivative</q> can be interpreted as a linear map
      <md>
        <mrow>D : \Poly_n \amp  \rightarrow \Poly_{n-1}</mrow>
        <mrow>p \amp  \mapsto p' \, </mrow>
      </md>.
      For example, <m>D(2x^3 - 6x + 2) = 6x^2 - 6</m>.
    </p>
    </statement>
  </example>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <ol label="(a)">
        <li><p> Why is <m>D</m> a map from <m>\Poly_n</m> to <m>\Poly_{n-1}</m>?</p></li>
        <li><p> Check that <m>D</m> is linear.</p></li>
      </ol>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <ol label="(a)">
          <li>
            <p>
              As you know from calculus, taking the derivative of a polynomial decreases every power of <m> x </m> by 1. So if <m> p </m> is in <m>\Poly_n </m>, then <m> p </m> has degree at most <m> n </m> . Therefore, its image under <m> D </m> has degree at most <m> n - 1</m>. Thus <m> p' </m> is in <m>\Poly_{n-1} </m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Let <m> p, q </m> be in <m> \Poly_n </m>. Then:
              <md>
                <mrow>
                  D(p + q) \amp = (p+q)'
                </mrow>
                <mrow> \amp = p' + q' \amp (\text{rule of differentiation})</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp = D(p) + D(q) </mrow>
              </md>
            </p>
            <p>
              Similarly,
              <md>
                <mrow> D(kp) \amp = (kp)' </mrow>
                <mrow> \amp = kp' \amp (\text{rule of differentiation})</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp = k D(p)</mrow>
              </md>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <example xml:id="antiderivative-as-linear-map-example">
    <title>Antiderivative as a linear map</title>
    <statement>
<!--
      <figure>
        <caption>Video recording for <xref ref="antiderivative-as-linear-map-example"/>.</caption>
        <video source="https://learn.sun.ac.za/pluginfile.php/1653776/mod_folder/content/0/Lec16Antiderivative.mp4" width="70%" preview="../latex/images/preview-doc-cam.jpg" onerror="this.src='Default.jpg'" />
      </figure>
-->
    <p>
      The operation <q>find the unique anti-derivative with zero constant term</q> can be interpreted as a linear map
      <md>
        <mrow>A : \Poly_n \amp  \rightarrow \Poly_{n+1}</mrow>
        <mrow>\ve{p} \amp  \mapsto \int_0^x \ve{p}(t) \, dt</mrow>
      </md>
      For example, <m>A(2x^3 - 6x + 2) = 4 x^4 - 3x^2 + 2x</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  </example>

  <exercise>
      <statement>
        <ol label="(a)">
          <li><p>
            Why is <m>A</m> a map from <m>\Poly_n</m> to <m>\Poly_{n+1}</m>?
          </p></li>
          <li><p>
            Check that <m>A</m> is indeed a linear map.
          </p></li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <ol label="(a)">
            <li>
              <p>
              You know from calculus that the antiderivative of a polynomial <m> \ve p </m> must always have degree one greater than <m> \ve p </m>. Hence <m> A </m> maps <m>\Poly_n</m> to <m> \Poly_{n+1}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Let <m> \ve p , \ve q </m> be in <m> \Poly_n </m>. Using the usual properties of the integral, we compute
                <md>
                  <mrow>
                  A(\ve p + \ve q) \amp = \int_0^x \ve p(t) + \ve q(t) \, dt = \int_0^x \ve p(t) \, dt + \int_0^x \ve q(t) \, dt </mrow>
                  <mrow> \amp = A(\ve p) + A(\ve q)</mrow>
                </md>.
                Similarly,
                <me>
                  A (k\ve p) = k\int_0^x \ve p(t) \, dt = \int_0^x k\ve p(t) \, dt = A(k\ve p).
                </me>
                </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>

  <example xml:id="shift_example">
    <title>Shift map</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
      Define the <q>shift forward by 1</q> map
      <md>
        <mrow>S : \Poly_n \amp  \rightarrow \Poly_n</mrow>
        <mrow>\ve{p} \amp  \mapsto S( \ve{p})</mrow>
      </md>
      by <m>S(\ve{p})(x) = \ve{p}(x-1)</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Consider the case <m>n=3</m>.
      In terms of the standard basis
      <me>
        \ve{p}_0 (x) = 1, \, \ve{p}_1 (x) = x, \, \ve{p}_2 (x) = x^2, \, \ve{p}_3 (x) = x^3
      </me>
      of <m>\Poly_3</m>, we have:
      <md>
        <mrow>S(\ve{p}_0) \amp = \ve{p}_0</mrow>
        <mrow>S(\ve{p}_1) \amp = \ve{p}_1 - \ve{p}_0</mrow>
        <mrow>S(\ve{p}_2) \amp = \ve{p}_2 - 2 \ve{p}_1 + \ve{p}_0</mrow>
        <mrow>S(\ve{p}_3) \amp = \ve{p}_3 - 3 \ve{p}_2 + 3 \ve{p}_1 - \ve{p}_0</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
    </statement>
  </example>

  <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Check that <m>S</m> is a linear map.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Let
          <md>
            <mrow>
            \ve p \amp = \sum_{j=0}^n a_j x^j \amp
            \ve q \amp= \sum_{j=0}^n b_j x^j
            </mrow>
          </md>
          We have to check
          <me>
            S(k \ve p ) = S\left( \sum_{j=0}^n ka_j x^j\right) = \sum_{j=0}^n ka_j (x-1)^j =  k \sum_{j=0}^n a_j (x-1)^j = kS(\ve p)
          </me>
          and
          <md>
            <mrow> S(\ve p + \ve q) \amp = S\left(\sum_{j=0}^n (a_j + b_j) x^j\right) = \sum_{j=0}^n (a_j + b_j) (x-1)^j </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp = \sum_{j=0}^n a_j (x-1)^j + \sum_{j=0}^n  b_j (x-1)^j = S(\ve p) + S(\ve q)</mrow>
          </md>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Check the formulas for <m>S(\ve{p}_0), S(\ve{p}_1), S(\ve{p}_2), S(\ve{p}_3),</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m> S(\ve p_0) = \ve p_0 </m> is trivial.
          Then we have
          <md>
            <mrow> S(\ve p_1) \amp = x-1 = \ve p_1 - \ve p_0 </mrow>
            <mrow> S(\ve p_2) \amp = (x-1)^2 = x^2 - 2x + 1 = \ve p_2 - 2\ve p_1 + \ve p_0 </mrow>
            <mrow>S(\ve p_3) \amp = (x-1)^3 = x^3 - 3x^2 + 3x - 1 = \ve{p}_3 - 3 \ve{p}_2 + 3 \ve{p}_1 - \ve{p}_0</mrow>
          </md>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>

  <example xml:id="grad_as_linear_map">
    <title>Gradient as a linear map</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Recall the vector space <m>\Poly_n</m> of polynomials in <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> (<xref ref="poly_many_variables_example"/>, dimension computed in <xref ref="dim_poly_many_variables"/>) and the vector space <m>\Vect_n (\mathbb{R}^2)</m> of polynomial vector fields on <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m> (<xref ref="poly_vector_fields_example"/>, dimension computed in <xref ref="dim_poly_vec_fields"/>).
      </p>

      <p>
        The operation <q>take the gradient</q> can be thought of as a linear map
        <md>
          <mrow> \nabla : \Poly_n[x,y] \amp \rightarrow \Vect_{n-1} (\mathbb{R}^2) </mrow>
          <mrow> f \amp \mapsto \nabla f </mrow>
        </md>
        This is a linear map because <m>\nabla(f + g) = \nabla f + \nabla g </m> and <m>\nabla (kf) = k \nabla f</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        For example,
        <me>
          \nabla(x + xy) = (1 + y, x).
        </me>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>

  <example>
  <title>Double integral as a linear map</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
      Let <m>D \subseteq \mathbb{R}^2</m> be a region in the plane. Integrating polynomial functions over <m>D</m> can be thought of as a linear map
      <md>
        <mrow> I : \Poly_n [x,y] \amp \mapsto \mathbb{R} </mrow>
        <mrow> f \amp \mapsto \iint_{D} f dA </mrow>
      </md>
      This is a linear map because
      <md>
        <mrow> \iint_D (f+g) dA \amp = \iint_D f dA + \iint_D g dA </mrow>
        <mrow> \iint_D kf \, dA \amp = k \iint_D f \, dA </mrow>
      </md>
    </p>

    <p>
      For example, let <m>D = \{ (x,y) : x^2 + y^2 \leq 1 \} </m>, and let <m>f = x^2</m>. Then
      <me>
        I(f) = \iint_D x^2 \, dA = \frac{\pi}{4}
      </me>
      as the reader will verify.
    </p>
   </statement>
  </example>

<example xml:id="initial_conditions_as_linear_map">
  <title>Initial conditions for differential equations as a linear map</title>
  <statement>
  <p>
    Let <m>V</m> be the vector space of solutions to a 2nd order linear homogenous ordinary differential equation on an interval <m>I</m>:
    <me>
      y^{''} + a_1(x) y'+ a_0(x) y = 0, \quad x \in I.
    </me>
    Fix a point <m>x_0 \in I</m>. Then we get a linear map
    <md>
      <mrow> T_{x_0} : \Col_2 \amp \rightarrow V </mrow>
      <mrow> \begin{bmatrix} a \\ b \end{bmatrix} \amp \mapsto \text{unique } y \in V \text{ such that } y(x_0) = a, y'(x_0)=b </mrow>
    </md>
  </p>

  <p>(Now is a good time to review <xref ref="diff_eqn_exist_unique"/> and <xref ref="geogebra_diff_eqn_1"/>.) </p>

  <p>
    This is illustrated in <xref ref="ode_lin_map"/> for the case of the differential equation
    <me>
       y^{''}  + xy = 0.
    </me>
    Drag the blue vector <m>\ve{v}</m> to see the effect on its image <m>T_{x_0}(\ve{v}) = y</m> in <m>V</m>. You can also change the value of <m>x_0</m>.
  </p>
    <figure xml:id="ode_lin_map">
      <interactive geogebra="https://www.geogebra.org/material/iframe/id/kxcmtv5t/width/800/height/909/border/888888/sfsb/true/smb/false/stb/false/stbh/false/ai/false/asb/false/sri/false/rc/false/ld/false/sdz/false/ctl/false" aspect="800:909" width="90%"/>
      <caption>GeoGebra App: Understanding the linear map <m>T</m>.</caption>
    </figure>
</statement>
</example>

</subsection>

<subsection>
  <title>Some results about linear maps</title>

  <lemma xml:id="lin_map_zero_to_zero">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Suppose <m>T : V \rightarrow W</m> is a linear map.
        Then

        <ol label="(a)">
          <li xml:id="lin_map_zero_to_zero_1">
            <p>
              <m>T(\ve{0}_V) = \ve{0}_W</m>;
            </p>
          </li>

          <li xml:id="lin_map_zero_to_zero_2">
            <p>
              <m>T(-\ve{v}) = - T(\ve{v})</m> for all vectors <m>\ve{v} \in V</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </lemma>

  <proof>
    <p>
      We leave (<xref ref="lin_map_zero_to_zero_1" text="local" />) as <xref ref="exercise-zero-maps-to-zero" /> and go to work as follows for (<xref ref="lin_map_zero_to_zero_2" text="local" />):
      <md>
        <mrow> T(-\ve{v}) \amp = T( (-1) \ve{v}) \amp  \text{(defn of } -\ve{v} \text{ in } V)</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = (-1) T(\ve{v}) \amp  (T \text{ is linear)}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = - T(\ve{v}) \amp  \text{(defn of }-T(\ve{v}) \text{ in } W)</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
  </proof>

  <p>
    The next result is very important.
    It tells us that if we know how a linear map <m>T</m> acts on a basis,
    then we know how it acts on the whole vector space
    (this is the <q>uniqueness</q> part).
    Moreover, we are free to write down any willy-nilly formula for what <m>T</m> does on the basis vectors,
    and we are guaranteed that this will always extend to a linear map defined on the whole vector space
    (this is the <q>existence</q> part).
  </p>

  <proposition xml:id="defining_linear_map_on_basis">
    <title>Sufficient to define a linear map on a basis</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Suppose <m>\basis{B} = \bopen \ve{e}_1, \ldots, \ve{e}_m \bclose</m> is a basis for <m>V</m> and
        <m>\ve{w}_1, \ldots, \ve{w}_m</m> are vectors in <m>W</m>.
        Then there exists a unique linear map <m>T : V \rightarrow W</m> such that
        <me>
          T(\ve{e}_i) = \ve{w}_i,  i = 1 \ldots m
        </me>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </proposition>

  <proof>
    <p>
      First we show the <em>existence</em> of such a linear map.
      To define a linear map <m>T</m>,
      we must define <m>T(\ve{v})</m> for each vector <m>\ve{v}</m>.
      We can write any <m>\ve{v}</m> uniquely as a linear combination of the vectors in the basis <m>\basis{B}</m>:
      <men xml:id="expansion_of_v_in_coords">
        \ve{v} = a_1 \ve{e}_1 + \cdots + a_m \ve{e}_m
      </men>.
      We define
      <men xml:id="formula_for_T">
        T(\ve{v}) := a_1 \ve{w}_1 + a_2 \ve{w}_2 + \cdots a_m \ve{w}_m
      </men>.
    </p>

    <p>
      We clearly have <m>T(\ve{e}_i) = \ve{w}_i</m>.
      To complete the proof of existence,
      we must show that <m>T</m> is linear.
      For that, also let <m>\ve{v}' = b_1\ve{e}_1+\cdots+b_m\ve{e}_m</m>. Then
      <md>
        <mrow>T(\ve{v} + \ve{v}') \amp = (a_1 + b_1) \ve{w}_1 + \cdots + (a_m + b_m) \ve{w}_m</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp =  \big(a_1 \ve{w}_1 + \cdots + a_m \ve{w}_m \big)  + \big(b_1 \ve{w}_1 + \cdots + b_m \ve{w}_m \big)</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = T(\ve{v}) + T(\ve{w})</mrow>
      </md>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Similarly, one can check that <m>T(k \ve{v}) = k T(\ve{v})</m>,
      which completes the proof of existence.
    </p>

    <p>
      Now we prove the <em>uniqueness</em> of such a linear map.
      Suppose that <m>S, T  : V \rightarrow W</m> are linear maps with
      <men xml:id="thing_to_satisfy">
        S(\ve{e}_i) = \ve{w}_i,  \text{ and }   T(\ve{e}_i) = \ve{w}_i,  i = 1 \ldots m
      </men>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Then,
      <md>
        <mrow>S (\ve{v}) \amp = S\big(a_1 \ve{e}_1 + \cdots + a_m \ve{e}_m\big)</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = a_1 S(\ve{e}_1) + \cdots + a_m S(\ve{e}_m) \amp (S \text{ is lineêr)}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = a_1 \ve{w}_1 + \cdots + a_m \ve{w}_m \amp  \text{(want } S(\ve{e}_i) = \ve{w}_i)</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = a_1 T(\ve{e}_1) + \cdots + a_m T(\ve{e}_m) \amp  \text{(want } T(\ve{e}_i) = \ve{w}_i)</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = T(a_1 \ve{e}_1 +  \cdots + a_m \ve{e}_m) \amp  (T \text{ is lineêr)}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = T(\ve{v})</mrow>
      </md>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Hence <m>S = T</m>,
      in other words the linear map satisfying <xref ref="thing_to_satisfy" /> is unique.
    </p>
  </proof>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        As an application of <xref ref="defining_linear_map_on_basis">Proposition</xref>,
        we can define a linear map
        <md>
          <mrow>T : \Col_2 \amp  \rightarrow \Fun(\mathbb{R})</mrow>
          <intertext>simply by defining its action on the standard basis of <m>\Col_2</m>. For instance, we may set</intertext>
          <mrow>\mat{e}_1 \amp  \rightarrow f_1</mrow>
          <mrow>\mat{e}_2 \amp  \rightarrow f_2</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>

      <p>
        The point is that we are free to send <m>\mat{e}_1</m> and
        <m>\mat{e}_2</m> to <em>any functions</em>
        <m>f_1</m> and <m>f_2</m> we like,
        and we are assured that this will give a well-defined linear map <m>T : \Col_2 \rightarrow \Fun(\mathbb{R})</m>.
        For instance, we might set
        <m>f_1 (x) = \sin x</m> and <m>f_2 (x) = |x|</m>.
        Then the general formula for <m>T</m> is
        <me>
          \left(T \begin{bmatrix} a \\ b \end{bmatrix}\right)(x) = a \sin x + b |x|
        </me>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>

  <example xml:id="rotation-map-example-complete">
    <title>Rotation map on standard basis</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let us compute the action of the <q>counterclockwise rotation by <m>\theta</m></q> map <m>R</m> from <xref ref="rotation_as_linear_map">Example</xref>
        with respect to the standard basis <m>\ve{e}_1, \ve{e}_2</m> of <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m>.
      </p>
      <sidebyside>
        <image width="40%">
          <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}\draw[<->] (-1, 0) -- (2, 0);
            \draw[<->] (0, -1) -- (0, 2);
            \draw[very thick, primaryColor, ->] (0, 0) -- (1.5, 0) node[below left] {$\ve{e}_1$};
            \draw[very thick, primaryColor, ->] (0,0) -- (30:1.5) node[right] {$R(\ve{e}_1)$};
            \draw (0:0.5) arc (0:30:0.5) node[above] {$\theta$};\end{tikzpicture}]]>
          </latex-image>
        </image>
        <image width="40%">
          <latex-image>
                    <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}\draw[<->] (-1, 0) -- (2, 0);
          \draw[<->] (0, -1) -- (0, 2);
          \draw[very thick, primaryColor, ->] (0, 0) -- (0, 1.5) node[right] {$\ve{e}_2$};
          \draw[very thick, primaryColor, ->] (0,0) -- (120:1.5) node[above] {$R(\ve{e}_2)$};
          \draw (90:0.5) arc (90:120:0.5) node[above, xshift=2pt, yshift=2pt] {$\theta$} ;\end{tikzpicture}]]>
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </sidebyside>

      <p>
        From the figure, we have:
        <md>
          <mrow>R(\ve{e}_1) \amp = (\cos \theta, \sin \theta) \amp  R(\ve{e}_2) \amp = (-\sin \theta, \cos \theta)</mrow>
        </md>
        so that
        <md>
          <mrow>R(\ve{e}_1) \amp =  \cos \theta \, \ve{e}_1 + \sin \theta\, \ve{e}_2,  R(\ve{e}_2) = -\sin \theta \, \ve{e}_1 +  \cos \theta\, \ve{e}_2</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>

      <p>
        Now that we know the action of <m>R</m> on the standard basis vectors,
        we can compute its action on an arbitrary vector <m>(x, y) \in \mathbb{R}^2</m>:
        <md>
          <mrow>R\left( (x,y)\right) \amp = R( x \ve{e}_1 + y \ve{e}_2 )</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = x R(\ve{e}_1) + y R(\ve{e}_2)</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = x (\cos \theta, \sin \theta) + y (-\sin \theta, \cos \theta)</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = (x \cos \theta - y \sin \theta, \, x \sin \theta + y \cos \theta)</mrow>
        </md>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>

</subsection>

<exercises>
 <exercise>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Determine whether the following are linear maps and motivate your answer:
    <ol label="(a)">
      <li>
        <m>T:\Row_3\to \Row_2</m> defined by <m>T(x,y,z) = (2x-y,x+y-z)</m>;
      </li>
      <li>
        <m>T:Func(\reals,\reals)\to \Row_2</m> defined by <m>T(f) = (f(1),f(0))</m>. (In other words, the input is a function from reals to reals and the output is the vector consisting of the values of <m>f</m> at 0 and 1.)
      </li>
      <li>
        <m>T:\Row_2\to \Row_2</m> defined by <m>T(x,y) = (x+1, y-2)</m>;
      </li>
      <li>
        <m>T:\Poly_2\to \Poly_3</m> defined by <m>T(p(x)) = xp(x)</m>. (I.e. the input polynomial gets multiplied by <m>x</m> and the result is the output.)
      </li>
      <li>
        <m>T:\Poly_2\to \Poly_4</m> defined by <m>T(p(x)) = (p(x))^2</m>;
      </li>
      <li>
        <m>T:\Poly_2\to \Poly_4</m> defined by <m>T(p(x)) = p(x^2)</m>. (What is the difference between this and the previous question?)
      </li>
      <li>
        <m>T:Func(\reals,\reals)\to Func(\reals,\reals)</m> defined by <m>T(f(x)) = f(x-1)</m>;
      </li>
      <li>
        <m>T:\Mat_{22}\to \reals</m> defined by <m>T\left(\begin{bmatrix} a\amp b\\c\amp d\end{bmatrix}\right) = ad-bc</m>.
      </li>
    </ol>
    </p>
  </statement>
</exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>V</m> be a vector space,
        and let <m>\ve{a} \neq \ve{0}</m> be a fixed vector.
        Let Define the map <m>T</m> as follows:
        <md>
          <mrow>T : V \amp \rightarrow V</mrow>
          <mrow>\ve{v} \amp  \mapsto \ve{a} + \ve{v}</mrow>
        </md>
        <ol label="(a)">
          <li>
            <p>
              Is <m>T</m> a linear map? (Yes or no)
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Prove your assertion from (a).
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <ol label="(a)">
          <li>
            <p>
              No.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              According to <xref ref = "lin_map_zero_to_zero"/>, <m> T(0) = 0 </m> is a necessary condition for <m>T</m> to be linear. However,
              <me>
              T(\ve 0) = \ve a + 0 = \ve a \neq \ve 0.
            </me>
            Hence <m> T </m> cannot be linear.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Consider the map <m>T : \mathbb{R}^3 \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^3</m> given by <m>T\left( (x,y,z) \right) = (z,x,y)</m>.

        <ol label="(a)">
          <li>
            <p>
              Is <m>T</m> a linear map? (Yes or no)
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Prove your assertion from (a).
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <ol label="(a)">
          <li>
            <p>
              Yes.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <md>
                <mrow> T\left((x,y,z) + (a,b,c)\right) \amp = T\left( (x+a,y+b , z + c) \right) = (z+c,x+a,y+b) </mrow>
                <mrow> \amp = (z,x,y) + (c,a,b)= T\left((x,y,z)\right) +  T\left((a,b,c)\right)
                </mrow>
              </md>
              <me>
                T(k(x,y,z)) = T(kx,ky,kz) = (kz,kx,ky) = k(z,x,y) = k T((x,y,z)).
              </me>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Define the <q>multiplication by <m>x^2</m></q> map
        <md>
          <mrow>M : \Poly_n \amp  \rightarrow \Poly_{n+2}</mrow>
          <mrow>\ve{p} \amp  \mapsto M(\ve{p})</mrow>
        </md>
        where <m>M(\ve{p})(x) = x^2 \ve{p}(x)</m>.

        <ol label="(a)">
          <li>
            <p>
              Why does <m>M</m> map from <m>\Poly_n</m> to <m>\Poly_{n+2}</m>?
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Prove that <m>M</m> is linear.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Compute the action of <m>M</m> in the standard basis for <m>\Poly_3</m>,
              as in <xref ref="shift_example">Example</xref>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <ol label="(a)">
          <li>
            <p>
              If <m> p(x) </m> has degree at most <m>n</m>, then <m> \ve q(x) := x^2 \ve p(x) </m> has degree at most <m>n+2</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              The proof is simple and follows from the usual properties of polynomials. Using the fact that multiplication of polynomials distributes over addition we compute
              <me>
                M(\ve p + \ve q)(x) = x^2(\ve p(x) + \ve q(x)) = x^2\ve p(x) + x^2\ve q(x) = M(\ve p)(x) + M(\ve q)(x)
              </me>.
              We may consider the scalar <m> k </m> as a constant polynomial. Thus, using the commutativity and associativity of polynomial multiplication we compute
              <me>
                M(k\ve p)(x) = x^2k\ve p (x) = k(x^2 \ve p(x)) = kM(\ve p)(x).
              </me>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <md>
                <mrow>M(\ve p_0) = x^2 1 = x^2 = \ve p_2 </mrow>
                <mrow>M(\ve p_1) = x^2 x = x^3 = \ve p_3 </mrow>
                <mrow>M(\ve p_2) = x^2 x^2 = x^4 = \ve p_4 </mrow>
                <mrow>M(\ve p_3) = x^2 x^3 = x^5 = \ve p_5 </mrow>
              </md>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Define the map
        <md>
        <mrow>  C : \Poly_n \amp \rightarrow \Trig_n </mrow>
        </md>
        by the formula
