  <exercise>
    <p>
      Determine the action of the gradient linear map
      <me>
        \nabla : \Poly_2[x,y] \rightarrow \Vect_1(\mathbb{R}^2)
      </me>
      from <xref ref="grad_as_linear_map"/> in terms of the standard bases
      <md>
        <mrow> \bopen q_1, q_2, q_3, q_4, q_5 \bclose  </mrow>
        <mrow> q_1 = 1, q_2 = x, q_3 = y, q_4 = x^2, q_5 = xy, q_6 = y^2</mrow>
      </md>
      of <m>\Poly_2</m> and
      <md>
        <mrow>  \bopen V_1, V_2, V_3, V_4, V_5, V_6 \bclose </mrow>
        <mrow>  V_1 = (1, 0), V_2 = (x, 0), V_3 = (y, 0) </mrow>
        <mrow> V_4 = (0, 1), V_5 = (0, x), V_6 = (0, y)</mrow>
      </md>
      of <m>\Vect_1(\mathbb{R}^2)</m>respectively.
    </p>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <p>
      Consider the following function:
      <md>
        <mrow> T : \Poly_2 \amp \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^2        </mrow>
        <mrow> p \amp \mapsto \begin{bmatrix} p(0) \\ p(1) \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
    <ol label="(a)">
      <li><p>
        Is <m>T</m> a linear map?
      </p></li>
      <li><p> Prove your assertion from (a).
      </p></li>
    </ol>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <p>
      Let <m>V</m> be the vector space of solutions to the differential equation
      <me>
        y^{(n)} + a_{n-1}(x) y^{(n-1)} + \cdots + a_1(x) y' + a_0(x) = 0
      </me>.
      Consider the <q>evaluate at <m>x=1</m></q> map
      <md>
        <mrow>T : V \amp \rightarrow \mathbb{R} </mrow>
        <mrow>y \amp \mapsto y(1)</mrow>
      </md>
      Is <m>T</m> a linear map? Prove your assertion.
    </p>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Define the <q>integrate over the interval
        <m>[-1,1]</m></q> map
        <md>
          <mrow>I : \Poly_n \amp  \rightarrow \mathbb{R}</mrow>
          <mrow>\ve{p} \amp  \mapsto \int_{-1}^{1} \ve{p}(x) \, dx</mrow>
        </md>
        <ol label="(a)">
          <li>
            <p>
              Prove that <m>I</m> is linear.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Compute the action of <m>I</m> with respect to the standard basis <m>\ve{p}_0, \ldots, \ve{p}_3</m> for <m>\Poly_3</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Compute the action of <m>I</m> with respect to the basis
              <m>\ve{q}_0, \ldots, \ve{q}_3</m> for <m>\Poly_3</m> from <xref ref="new_basis_for_poly_3">Example</xref>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <ol label="(a)">

          <li>
            <p>
            We use the properties of the integral.
            <md>
              <mrow>
              I(\ve p + \ve q) \amp = \int_{-1}^1 \left( \ve p(x) + \ve q(x)\right) \, dx</mrow>
              <mrow> =  \int_{-1}^1 \ve p(x) \, dx +
              \int_{-1}^1 \ve q(x) \, dx = I(\ve p) + I(\ve q)</mrow>
            </md>.
            <me>
              I(k\ve p )  = \int_{-1}^1 k\ve p(x) \, dx = k\int_{-1}^1 \ve p(x) \, dx = kI(\ve p)
            </me>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
            <md>
              <mrow>I(\ve p_0) \amp = \int_{-1}^1 1 dx = x\rvert^1_{-1} = 2 </mrow>
              <mrow> I(\ve p_1) \amp = \int_{-1}^1 x dx = \frac{1}{2}x^2 \rvert^1_{-1} = 0</mrow>
              <mrow> I(\ve p_2) \amp = \int_{-1}^1 x^2 dx = \frac{1}{3}x^3 \rvert^1_{-1} = \frac{2}{3} </mrow>
              <mrow> I(\ve p_3) \amp = \int_{-1}^1 x^3 dx = \frac{1}{4}x^4 \rvert^1_{-1} = 0</mrow>
            </md>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              We use the results above:
              <md>
                <mrow>
                I(\ve q_0) \amp = \int_{-1}^1 1 dx = x\rvert^1_{-1} = 2</mrow>
                <mrow> I(\ve q_1) \amp = \int_{-1}^1 x dx = \frac{1}{2}x^2 \rvert^1_{-1} = 0</mrow>
                <mrow> I(\ve q_2) \amp = \int_{-1}^1 2x^2 - 1 dx = 2\int_{-1}^1 x^2 dx - \int_{-1}^1 1 =  \frac{4}{3} - 2 = -\frac{2}{3} </mrow>
                <mrow> I(\ve q_3) \amp = \int_{-1}^1 4x^3 - 3x dx = 4\int_{-1}^1 x^3 dx - 3\int_{-1}^1 x dx = 4.0 - 3.0 = 0</mrow>
              </md>.
            </p>
          </li>

        </ol>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Compute the action of the differentiation map
        <m>D : \Poly_4 \rightarrow \Poly_3</m> from <xref ref="diff_of_poly">Example</xref>
        with respect to the standard bases of these two vector spaces.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <md>
          <mrow>
          D(\ve p_0) \amp = D(1) = 0  </mrow>
          <mrow> D(\ve p_1) \amp = D(x)= 1 = \ve p_0 </mrow>
          <mrow> D(\ve p_2) \amp = D(x^2) = 2x = 2\ve p_1 </mrow>
          <mrow> D(\ve p_3) \amp = D(x^3) = 3x^2 = 3\ve p_2 </mrow>
          <mrow> D(\ve p_4) \amp = D(x^4) = 4x^3 = 4 \ve p_3</mrow>
        </md>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Consider the cross-product linear map
        <m>C : \mathbb{R}^3 \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^3</m> from <xref ref="cross_prod_as_linear_map">Example</xref>
        in the case <m>\ve{w} = (1, 2, 3)</m>.
        Compute the action of <m>C</m> with respect to the standard basis of <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <md>
          <mrow>C((1,0,0)) = (1,2,3) \times (1,0,0) = (0,3,-2)</mrow>
          <mrow>C((0,1,0)) = (1,2,3) \times (0,1,0) = (-3,0,1)</mrow>
          <mrow>C((0,0,1)) = (1,2,3) \times (0,0,1) = (2,-1,0)</mrow>
        </md>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>T:V\to W</m> be a linear map and suppose that <m>T(\ve{v}_1)=\ve{w}_1</m> and <m>T(\ve{v}_2)=\ve{w}_2</m>. Prove that <m>T(4\ve{v}_1-\ve{v}_2)=4\ve{w}_1-\ve{w}_2</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="exercise-zero-maps-to-zero">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Prove that for any linear map <m>T:V \to W</m> we have <m>T(\ve{0}_V)=\ve{0}_W</m>, where <m>\ve{0}_V</m> is the zero vector in <m>V</m> and <m>\ve{0}_W</m> is the zero vector in <m>W</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <md>
          <mrow>   T(\ve{0}_V) \amp = T( 0 \ve{0}_V) \amp  \text{(R8 applied to } \ve{v} = \ve{0}_V \in V)</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = 0T(\ve{0}_V) \amp  (T \text{ is linear)}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = \ve{0}_W \amp  \text{(R8 applied to } \ve{v} = T(\ve{0}_V) \in W)</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>T:V \to W</m> be a linear map between two vector spaces.
        Suppose that <m>V</m> is finite-dimensional and that
        <m>\basis{B} = \bopen \ve b_1,\ldots, \ve b_n\bclose</m>
        is a basis for <m>V</m>.
        If <m>T(\ve b_i)=0</m> (the zero vector in <m>W</m>)
        for all the basis elements <m>\ve b_i</m>,
        then <m>T</m> is the zero map (i.e. it maps all vectors to <m>\ve{0}</m>).
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>V</m> and <m>W</m> be vector spaces and <m>T:V\to W</m> a linear map.
        Show that if the vectors <m>\ve v_1,\ldots, \ve v_m</m>
        are linearly dependent in <m>V</m>,
        then the vectors <m>T(\ve v_1),\ldots, T(\ve v_m)</m> are linearly dependent in <m>W</m>.
        (Is it true that if the <m>\ve v_i</m> are linearly independent,
        then the <m>T(\ve v_i)</m> are linearly independent?)
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

<exercisegroup>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Let <m>\mathcal{L}(V,\reals)</m> denote the set of all <em>linear</em> maps from <m>V</m> to <m>\reals</m>.
      We will show that this set has the natural structure of a vector space!
    </p>
    <p>
      If you have two linear maps <m>T_1:V\to \reals</m> and <m>T_2:V\to \reals</m>,
      then we can define their sum as the function that maps any
      <m>\ve v\in V</m> to <m>T_1(\ve v)+T_2(\ve v)</m>.
      Note that this is exactly the same as the addition of two functions.
    </p>
    <p>
      We can also define a scalar multiplication by defining the map
      <m>c\smul T</m> to be the map defined by <m>(c\smul T)(\ve v) = c\smul T(\ve v)</m>.
      Again, note that scalar multiplication is defined in the same way as it was for functions.
    </p>
    <p>
      So we can add any two linear maps <m>T_1,T_2</m> to get a map <m>T_1+T_2</m>
      and we can multiply any linear map <m>T</m> by a scalar to get a map <m>c\smul T</m>.
      Your first aim is to show that those maps are also linear maps.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Prove that if <m>V</m> is a vector space,
        then the set of all linear maps from <m>V</m> to <m>\mathbb R</m>,
        denoted <m>\mathcal L (V,\mathbb R)</m>,
        is itself a vector space.
        Since we already know that the set of all
        real valued functions from <m> V </m> to <m>\mathbb R</m> forms a vector space,
        you will only have to show that <m>\mathcal L (V,\mathbb R)</m>
        contains the function <m>\ve 0</m>, and is closed
        under both addition and scalar multiplication.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        For all <m>\ve v,\ve w \in  V</m>, for all <m>S, T \in \mathcal L (V,\mathbb R)</m> and for all <m>a , b \in \mathbb R</m>:
      <ol label="(a)">
        <li>
          <p>
            <md>
              <mrow>\ve 0(\ve v + \ve w) = 0 = \ve 0\ve v + \ve 0\ve w </mrow>
              <mrow>0(a\ve v) = 0 = a \ve 0 </mrow>
            </md>
            and hence <m> \ve 0 \in \mathcal L (V,\mathbb R)</m>.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <md>
              <mrow>(a S)(\ve v + \ve W) = a(S (\ve v + \ve w )) = a(S \ve v+ S\ve w) = (a S)\ve v + (a S) \ve w</mrow>
              <mrow>(a S)(b \ve v) = (ab) S \ve v = b( a S \ve v) </mrow>
            </md>
            and hence <m> a S \in \mathcal L (V,\mathbb R)</m>.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <md>
              <mrow>(S + T)(\ve v + \ve w) = S(\ve v+ \ve w) + T(\ve v + \ve w) </mrow>
              <mrow>= S\ve v + S \ve w + T \ve v + T \ve w  = (S + T)\ve v + (S + T)\ve w </mrow>
              <mrow>(S + T)(a \ve v) = S (a \ve v) + T(a \ve w ) = aS\ve v+  aT \ve w = a(S+T)\ve v</mrow>
            </md>
            and hence <m> S + T  \in \mathcal L (V,\mathbb R)</m>.
          </p>
        </li>

      </ol>
    </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        If <m>V </m> is a finite dimensional vector space, find a basis for <m> \mathcal L(V , \mathbb R) </m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Show that for every element <m>\ve v\in V</m> the map <m>\phi_{\ve v}:\mathcal{L}(V,\reals)\to \reals</m> defined by <m>\phi_{\ve v}(T)  = T(\ve v)</m> is linear.
      </p>
      <p>
        This problem is a bit harder, because it is
        something that might take long to get used to.
        You should be thinking of a linear map <m>T</m>
        as a single object that can be used as the input to this map <m>\phi_{\ve v}</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <title> Not for the faint-hearted</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Again, let <m>V</m> be a vector space.
        Let <m>W</m> be the vector space <m>\mathcal{L}(V,\reals)</m>.
        So its elements are linear maps from <m>V</m> to <m>\reals</m>.
        Now consider the map <m>\Phi:V \to \mathcal{L}(W,\reals)</m>
        defined by <m>\Phi(\ve v) = \phi_{\ve v}</m>.
        (Recall from the previous problem that <m>\phi_{\ve v}</m>
        is a linear map from <m>\mathcal{L}(V,\reals)</m>
        to <m>\reals</m>, so it really does belong to <m>\mathcal{L}(W,\reals)</m>,
        so the definition of <m>\Phi</m> makes sense.)
        Prove that <m>\Phi</m> is also a linear map.
      </p>
      <p>
        Bonus: If <m>V</m> is finite-dimensional, prove that <m>\Phi</m> is an isomorphism (<xref ref="def-isomorphism" />).
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

</exercisegroup>

</exercises>

